  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: The Teddy Coat Has a Schedule" imageAlt="Cavachon puppy being brushed through its soft wavy coat" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>The Cavachon's soft, low-shedding coat runs on the same deal as its cousin crosses: hair that doesn't fall out stays in and tangles instead. The schedule that keeps it comfortable in our humidity: a brush every other day, a comb-through to the skin weekly, and a salon groom every 4 to 6 weeks; nearly every Singapore Cavachon lives happily in a puppy cut.</p>
      <p>Two ten-second habits round it out: a weekly lift-look-sniff of those drop ears, warmth plus humidity is how ear trouble starts, and a daily eye wipe on light-coloured faces to stay ahead of tear staining. The cleanser and wipes are already in your starter kit.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Cavachon Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Cavachon puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Cavachon goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. And because honest pages answer the question buyers actually have: yes, the Cavalier parent carries a known heart condition (mitral valve disease), and crossing to a <a href="/puppies/cavalier-king-charles-spaniel" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">Cavalier</a> line lowers, but does not erase, that inheritance. The practical habit is the same one we give Cavalier owners: from around age five, make sure the annual vet visit includes a proper listen to the heart. Early detection changes everything, and most Cavachons live their 12 to 15 years untroubled.</p>
      <p>The rest is routine small-breed fare: weekly ear care, kneecaps (patellar luxation), and dental habits from day one. Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. See the <a href="/learn/puppy-health" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Cavachon's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Cavachon puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Cavachon explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about <a href="/delivery" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and close. This cross settles through proximity: the playpen where it can see people, a fixed feeding routine, and the toilet pads where we placed them. Some night whimpering is normal adjustment.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks, and two habits start now while they're easy: book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer, and practise short, boring departures, five minutes at a time, so alone-time skills grow before they're ever needed. See <a href="/free-training" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

